---

<Layout title="Number Theory Ch.6 — Quadratic Residues" favicon="#">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/number-theory/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Number Theory</a>

    <h1>Quadratic Residues</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Jim Hefferon &middot; Elementary Number Theory &middot; <a href="https://jheffero.w3.uvm.edu/numbertheory/">Ch. 6</a></p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">A <strong>quadratic residue</strong> mod p is a nonzero number that is a perfect square mod p. Exactly half the nonzero residues are squares. The Legendre symbol encodes which are which, and quadratic reciprocity reveals a deep symmetry between different primes.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- SVG: Quadratic residues mod 13 -->
    <h3>Squares mod p</h3>
    <p>For a prime p, the nonzero residues mod p split evenly: (p-1)/2 are quadratic residues (squares), and (p-1)/2 are non-residues. This is because squaring is two-to-one: a^2 &#x2261; (-a)^2 (mod p).</p>

    <div class="flex justify-center my-6">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 420 100" class="w-full max-w-md" style="font-family: ui-monospace, monospace;">
        <text x="210" y="15" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.35">Quadratic residues mod 13 (squares highlighted)</text>
        <!-- Numbers 1-12, QRs highlighted: 1,3,4,9,10,12 -->
        <rect x="10" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="24" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">1</text>
        <text x="56" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">2</text>
        <rect x="74" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="88" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">3</text>
        <rect x="106" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="120" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">4</text>
        <text x="152" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">5</text>
        <text x="184" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">6</text>
        <text x="216" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">7</text>
        <text x="248" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">8</text>
        <rect x="266" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="280" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">9</text>
        <rect x="298" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="312" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">10</text>
        <text x="344" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="currentColor" font-size="12" fill-opacity="0.2">11</text>
        <rect x="362" y="28" width="28" height="28" rx="3" fill="#facc15" fill-opacity="0.15"/>
        <text x="376" y="47" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="12">12</text>
        <!-- Labels -->
        <text x="210" y="82" text-anchor="middle" fill="#facc15" font-size="10" fill-opacity="0.6">QR mod 13: 1, 3, 4, 9, 10, 12 (6 of 12)</text>
      </svg>
    </div>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Find quadratic residues mod p
(define (quadratic-residues p)
  (let loop ((a 1) (qrs (list)))
    (if (>= a p)
        (sort (delete-duplicates qrs) <)
        (loop (+ a 1)
              (cons (modulo (* a a) p) qrs)))))

(define (delete-duplicates lst)
  (cond ((null? lst) lst)
        ((member (car lst) (cdr lst))
         (delete-duplicates (cdr lst)))
        (else (cons (car lst)
                    (delete-duplicates (cdr lst))))))

(display "QR mod 13: ") (display (quadratic-residues 13)) (newline)
(display "QR mod 7:  ") (display (quadratic-residues 7)) (newline)
(display "QR mod 11: ") (display (quadratic-residues 11))
`} />


    <!-- Legendre symbol and Euler's criterion -->
    <h3>Legendre symbol and Euler's criterion</h3>
    <p>The Legendre symbol (a/p) equals 1 if a is a QR mod p, -1 if not, and 0 if p divides a. Euler's criterion computes it: (a/p) &#x2261; a^((p-1)/2) (mod p). This is a fast test for whether a number is a square mod p.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Euler's criterion: (a/p) = a^((p-1)/2) mod p
(define (mod-pow base exp mod)
  (cond ((= exp 0) 1)
        ((even? exp)
         (let ((half (mod-pow base (quotient exp 2) mod)))
           (modulo (* half half) mod)))
        (else (modulo (* base (mod-pow base (- exp 1) mod)) mod))))

(define (legendre a p)
  (let ((result (mod-pow a (quotient (- p 1) 2) p)))
    (if (= result (- p 1)) -1 result)))

(display "(2/7) = ") (display (legendre 2 7)) (newline)   ; 1 (QR)
(display "(3/7) = ") (display (legendre 3 7)) (newline)   ; -1 (NR)
(display "(4/13) = ") (display (legendre 4 13)) (newline)  ; 1
(display "(5/13) = ") (display (legendre 5 13)) (newline)  ; -1
(display "(7/13) = ") (display (legendre 7 13))             ; -1
`} />

    <div class="python-block my-2" style="display:none">
      <Repl client:visible initialCode={`# Legendre symbol via Euler's criterion
def legendre(a, p):
    result = pow(a, (p - 1) // 2, p)
    return -1 if result == p - 1 else result

print(f"(2/7) = {legendre(2, 7)}")
print(f"(3/7) = {legendre(3, 7)}")
print(f"(4/13) = {legendre(4, 13)}")
print(f"(5/13) = {legendre(5, 13)}")

# Quadratic residues mod p
def qr(p):
    return sorted(set(pow(a, 2, p) for a in range(1, p)))

print(f"QR mod 13: {qr(13)}")
`} />
    </div>


    <!-- Quadratic reciprocity -->
    <h3>Quadratic reciprocity (statement)</h3>
    <p>For distinct odd primes p and q: (p/q)(q/p) = (-1)^((p-1)/2 * (q-1)/2). In words: p is a square mod q and q is a square mod p, unless both are 3 mod 4, in which case exactly one is. This is the "golden theorem" that <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Gauss</a> proved eight different ways.</p>

    <SchemeRepl client:visible initialCode={`; Verify quadratic reciprocity for small primes
(define (mod-pow base exp mod)
  (cond ((= exp 0) 1)
        ((even? exp)
         (let ((half (mod-pow base (quotient exp 2) mod)))
           (modulo (* half half) mod)))
        (else (modulo (* base (mod-pow base (- exp 1) mod)) mod))))

(define (legendre a p)
  (let ((r (mod-pow a (quotient (- p 1) 2) p)))
    (if (= r (- p 1)) -1 r)))

(define (check-reciprocity p q)
  (let* ((lpq (legendre p q))
         (lqp (legendre q p))
         (sign (if (and (= 3 (modulo p 4)) (= 3 (modulo q 4))) -1 1)))
    (display "(") (display p) (display "/") (display q) (display ")=")
    (display lpq) (display "  (") (display q) (display "/") (display p)
    (display ")=") (display lqp)
    (display "  product=") (display (* lpq lqp))
    (display "  predicted=") (display sign) (newline)))

(check-reciprocity 3 5)
(check-reciprocity 3 7)
(check-reciprocity 5 7)
(check-reciprocity 3 11)
(check-reciprocity 5 13)
`} />


    <PrevNext prev={{ href: "/reading/number-theory/numthy-05/", label: "Chinese Remainder Theorem" }} next={{ href: "/reading/number-theory/numthy-07/", label: "Primitive Roots" }} />

  </main>
</Layout>
